04286nam a22007335i 9780801465994DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20122017nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979684344  a97808014659947 a10.7591/97808014659942doi  a(DE-B1597)478408  a(OCoLC)961556292  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aBR190b.R43 2016 7aHIS0020202bisacsh04a276.1022231 aRebillard, Éric, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aChristians and Their Many Identities in Late Antiquity, North Africa, 200-450 CE /cÉric Rebillard. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2012] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (144 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Primary Sources -- tIntroduction -- t1. Setting the Stage: Carthage at the End of the Second Century -- t2. Persecution and the Limits of Religious Allegiance -- t3. Being Christian in the Age of Augustine -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor too long, the study of religious life in Late Antiquity has relied on the premise that Jews, pagans, and Christians were largely discrete groups divided by clear markers of belief, ritual, and social practice. More recently, however, a growing body of scholarship is revealing the degree to which identities in the late Roman world were fluid, blurred by ethnic, social, and gender differences. Christianness, for example, was only one of a plurality of identities available to Christians in this period.In Christians and Their Many Identities in Late Antiquity, North Africa, 200–450 CE, Éric Rebillard explores how Christians in North Africa between the age of Tertullian and the age of Augustine were selective in identifying as Christian, giving salience to their religious identity only intermittently. By shifting the focus from groups to individuals, Rebillard more broadly questions the existence of bounded, stable, and homogeneous groups based on Christianness. In emphasizing that the intermittency of Christianness is structurally consistent in the everyday life of Christians from the end of the second to the middle of the fifth century, this book opens a whole range of new questions for the understanding of a crucial period in the history of Christianity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aChristian lifexHistoryxEarly church, ca. 30-600. 0aChristian lifexHistoryyEarly church, ca. 30-600. 0aChurch historyxPrimitive and early church, ca. 30-600. 0aChurch historyyPrimitive and early church, ca. 30-600. 4aAncient History & Classical Studies. 4aHistory. 4aReligious Studies. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / Rome.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146599440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801465994423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801465994/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK